Male genitalia:
Median lobe consisting of a few sclerites, well separated apically (
Fig. 14A, B, C
). Shape of paramere narrowly triangular, with very dense, strong, long setae along dorsal margin (
Fig. 14D
).

The species is widely distributed in the northern half of Australia. Records are from the Northern Territory (inland to the East MacDonnell Ranges), north-western Australia (Kimberley region and the Pilbara), and Queensland south to Brisbane (
Fig. 23
).
